WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:30.663 --> 00:00:32.599
Vincent J Musi:
So our relationship with animals

00:00:32.599 --> 00:00:35.368
<i> is constantly evolving.</i>

00:00:35.368 --> 00:00:38.003
<i> For the longest time science
 could just never accept</i>

00:00:38.003 --> 00:00:41.074
<i> what most pet owners know
is that animals think and feel.</i>

00:00:41.074 --> 00:00:43.242
<i> But proving that they have
 thoughts and emotions</i>

00:00:43.242 --> 00:00:45.712
<i> is a lot of what this work
 is about.</i>

00:00:45.712 --> 00:00:48.247
<i> The question for me next
 is really about</i>

00:00:48.247 --> 00:00:50.816
<i> over these 10,000 years
 how does an animal</i>

00:00:50.816 --> 00:00:53.252
<i> that's intended
 for the dining room,</i>

00:00:53.252 --> 00:00:56.055
<i> how does it go
 to the living room?</i>

00:00:56.055 --> 00:01:02.594
( applause )

00:01:02.594 --> 00:01:05.598
Vincent J Musi:
Thank you, you're very kind.

00:01:05.598 --> 00:01:07.934 line:0%
It all started for me
when I bought a haunted house.

00:01:07.934 --> 00:01:09.569 line:0%
(laughter)

00:01:09.569 --> 00:01:11.604 line:0%
It's true. That's what
the neighbors told me,

00:01:11.604 --> 00:01:12.972
but it was after
I bought the house.

00:01:12.972 --> 00:01:15.207
Here's a photograph of it.
(laughter)

00:01:15.207 --> 00:01:17.243
<i> The previous tenants
 had heard all this scratching</i>

00:01:17.243 --> 00:01:20.012
<i> and kicking and rumbling and
 creaking all around the house,</i>

00:01:20.012 --> 00:01:22.048
<i> they thought it was
 the ghost of Edgar Allan Poe,</i>

00:01:22.048 --> 00:01:25.351
<i> who lived in the neighborhood,
 where I live now.</i>

00:01:25.351 --> 00:01:29.656
So I did what any sane person
would do, I called an exorcist.

00:01:29.656 --> 00:01:33.259
<i> His name was Mike Hughes.
 And he's a trapper</i>

00:01:33.259 --> 00:01:35.494
<i> and a specialist
 in nuisance wildlife.</i>

00:01:35.494 --> 00:01:37.897
So, he managed to get
all the ghosts out of my house,

00:01:37.897 --> 00:01:40.433
the squirrels, the opossums,
the nine raccoons,

00:01:40.433 --> 00:01:42.101
the birds, the rats.

00:01:42.101 --> 00:01:43.803
It was either that or
to designate

00:01:43.803 --> 00:01:46.406
it a national wildlife refuge.
(laughter)

00:01:46.406 --> 00:01:48.507
Now Mike had quite a menagerie
at his own home

00:01:48.507 --> 00:01:50.442
and I was curious,
so I photographed him.

00:01:50.442 --> 00:01:52.512
And some of his animals
were opossums,

00:01:52.512 --> 00:01:55.448
an albino raccoon,
and this iguana.

00:01:55.448 --> 00:01:57.850
So I asked around
some of my colleagues.

00:01:57.850 --> 00:01:58.985
A lot of the guys do this.

00:01:59.051 --> 00:02:01.721
<i> We're trying to do this
eye contact thing, it's simple.</i>

00:02:01.721 --> 00:02:04.023
<i> We bring an animal,
 we put it on a seamless.</i>

00:02:04.023 --> 00:02:05.691
I said, "What do we do?"
And they said,

00:02:05.691 --> 00:02:08.060
"You know, all animals
are food motivated.

00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:10.296
All you have to do
is really kinda provide

00:02:10.296 --> 00:02:13.098
the set and this is
going to work out for you.

00:02:13.098 --> 00:02:15.535
<i> I thought, okay, that's cool.
 Well, mistakes were made.</i>

00:02:15.535 --> 00:02:20.606
(audience roaring
with laughter)

00:02:20.606 --> 00:02:22.107
<i> Yeah.</i>

00:02:22.107 --> 00:02:24.277
<i> The idea here was
 to photograph these--</i>

00:02:24.277 --> 00:02:26.345
(audience laughter)

00:02:26.345 --> 00:02:30.216
<i>Yeah, exactly, these superstars</i>

00:02:30.216 --> 00:02:32.284
<i> of the animal cognition.
 These are famous animals.</i>

00:02:32.284 --> 00:02:34.186
<i> Years of research
 had been done with them.</i>

00:02:34.186 --> 00:02:37.056
<i> Books had been
 written about them,
 scientific careers...</i>

00:02:37.056 --> 00:02:38.624
And I was going to become

00:02:38.624 --> 00:02:40.760
the Annie Leibovitz
of animal photographs.

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:42.061
(laughter)

00:02:42.061 --> 00:02:45.898
And it was going to be all about
eye contact and lighting. Right?

00:02:45.898 --> 00:02:48.634
Well, it's hard to do that when
an animal won't look at you.

00:02:48.634 --> 00:02:50.302
(laughter)

00:02:50.302 --> 00:02:52.404
<i> And with some animals,
 like this lemur,</i>

00:02:52.404 --> 00:02:54.941
<i> every time I picked up
 the camera, boom! He was gone.</i>

00:02:54.941 --> 00:02:58.077
<i> He'd shoot away.
 And my career, like the lemur,</i>

00:02:58.077 --> 00:02:59.579
<i> was vanishing
 before my eyes.</i>

00:02:59.579 --> 00:03:00.679
(laughter)

00:03:00.679 --> 00:03:02.848
You don't get
a lot of second chances.

00:03:02.848 --> 00:03:04.617
And I thought,
why is this happening?

00:03:04.617 --> 00:03:07.119
Why am I being punished here?
What have I done wrong?

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:10.423
I went all the way to Austria
to photograph this Marmoset.

00:03:10.423 --> 00:03:11.657
<i> His name is Momo.</i>

00:03:11.657 --> 00:03:14.393
<i> He's really smart.
 Okay, big deal.</i>

00:03:14.393 --> 00:03:17.263
And he smells really bad.
(laughter)

00:03:17.263 --> 00:03:19.965
<i> And his head
 is the size of a walnut.</i>

00:03:19.965 --> 00:03:22.534
And he hates me.
(laughter)

00:03:22.534 --> 00:03:23.903
<i> See, it looks calm to you,
 doesn't it?</i>

00:03:23.903 --> 00:03:25.672
<i> No, it's not.</i>

00:03:25.672 --> 00:03:27.707
(audience roaring
with laughter)

00:03:27.707 --> 00:03:30.075
He's peeing on me.
(laughter)

00:03:30.075 --> 00:03:31.677
<i> He's peeing on my equipment,</i>

00:03:31.677 --> 00:03:34.447
<i> and he's telling his
 Marmoset friends to pee on me</i>

00:03:34.447 --> 00:03:36.682
and pee on my equipment.
(laughter)

00:03:36.682 --> 00:03:39.752
<i> And he screamed at me
 and he wouldn't stop.</i>

00:03:39.752 --> 00:03:42.621
<i> And he told his friends
 to scream at me.</i>

00:03:42.621 --> 00:03:44.090
And... I began to think that

00:03:44.090 --> 00:03:46.993
<i> even fish were screaming at me
 from under water.</i>

00:03:46.993 --> 00:03:50.863
<i> This is a Gunnison's
 prairie dog, and he
 screamed at me too.</i>

00:03:50.863 --> 00:03:53.131
<i> Scientists believe these guys
 have language ability,</i>

00:03:53.131 --> 00:03:54.366
<i> sophisticated stuff, right.</i>

00:03:54.366 --> 00:03:56.336
It's not like,
"Aah! Bad things
are happening...

00:03:56.336 --> 00:03:58.471
It's like, "There's a guy
from National Geographic

00:03:58.471 --> 00:03:59.905
and he's gonna come here
and take our picture."

00:03:59.905 --> 00:04:01.541
This guy screamed at me
on the phone.

00:04:01.541 --> 00:04:03.642
(laughter)

00:04:03.642 --> 00:04:07.380
And, he... he's a rescued
prairie dog from Phoenix.

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:09.949
He was hit by a car and
his name is Speed-bump.

00:04:09.949 --> 00:04:11.750
(laughter)

00:04:11.750 --> 00:04:14.320
And he lives in Wabash, Indiana.

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:16.355
It's like I didn't know what to
do, I couldn't take it anymore.

00:04:16.355 --> 00:04:18.958
I started to scream at him,
back at him.

00:04:18.958 --> 00:04:21.560
And I started to interview him
like... like a press conference,

00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:24.329
rapid fire. "Mr. Bump,
how are the winters in Wabash?

00:04:24.329 --> 00:04:25.898
What do you think?"
All this kind of stuff,

00:04:25.898 --> 00:04:27.767
and I sang to him.
I did everything I could,

00:04:27.767 --> 00:04:29.936
and all of a sudden
he just stopped.

00:04:29.936 --> 00:04:32.871
(audience roaring
with laughter)

00:04:32.871 --> 00:04:36.675
So, you see, with Speed-bump,

00:04:36.675 --> 00:04:38.744
I discovered
my inner Doctor Dolittle

00:04:38.744 --> 00:04:40.679
and I embarked
on this new career,

00:04:40.679 --> 00:04:42.848
if I could just talk
to the animals.

00:04:42.848 --> 00:04:45.985
Show this respect and patience,

00:04:45.985 --> 00:04:48.220
things I didn't have much of
to be honest with you,

00:04:48.220 --> 00:04:50.723
I might find
what I was looking for.

00:04:50.723 --> 00:04:54.527
<i> Now, this is Kanzi.
 He was a real test for sure.</i>

00:04:54.527 --> 00:04:56.429
<i> Does anybody know Kanzi,
 he's a Bonobo.</i>

00:04:56.429 --> 00:04:57.729
<i> He's a pygmy chimpanzee.</i>

00:04:57.729 --> 00:05:00.666
<i> He understands
 about 3,000 spoken words.</i>

00:05:00.666 --> 00:05:01.934
<i> It's incredible.</i>

00:05:01.934 --> 00:05:03.669
<i> So, now he communicates
 with humans</i>

00:05:03.669 --> 00:05:05.804
<i> using this vocabulary
 that's drawn</i>

00:05:05.804 --> 00:05:08.540
<i> from like 350 symbols.
 It's lexigrams.</i>

00:05:08.540 --> 00:05:12.044
And, they're printed
on a sort of like, uh,

00:05:12.044 --> 00:05:13.546
place mat,
laminated thing.

00:05:13.546 --> 00:05:16.115
He walks around with it and
he makes complex sentences.

00:05:16.115 --> 00:05:18.951
"Kanzi wants this now
with this person there."

00:05:18.951 --> 00:05:21.386
It's not like... pointing
to the thing.

00:05:21.386 --> 00:05:24.189
And the lexigram for an orange
may not look like an orange.

00:05:24.189 --> 00:05:26.458
It's real sophisticated stuff.

00:05:26.458 --> 00:05:27.960
So, I got there and they said,

00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:31.230
"What... what... what have you
brought for Kanzi?" I said,

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:34.901
"I didn't bring anything.
I brought my lights."

00:05:34.901 --> 00:05:36.569
So, we have to ask
his permission.

00:05:36.569 --> 00:05:38.070
And we have to ask
him what he'd like.

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:40.239
And so they, you know...
(does hand movements)

00:05:40.239 --> 00:05:43.643
And Kanzi...
(does hand movements)

00:05:43.643 --> 00:05:46.412
And, they interpreted
that as "Kanzi would like

00:05:46.412 --> 00:05:49.382
Starbucks coffee for he
and his Bonobo friends."

00:05:49.382 --> 00:05:51.217
(audience roaring
with laughter)

00:05:51.217 --> 00:05:52.918
And so I had to send
my assistant back

00:05:52.918 --> 00:05:57.923
into town to get six grande
coffees with the simple syrup,

00:05:57.923 --> 00:05:59.391
for him and his Bonobo friends.

00:05:59.391 --> 00:06:00.993
And, Kanzi every once
in a while,

00:06:00.993 --> 00:06:02.561
will do this sort of thing
where he'll go...

00:06:02.561 --> 00:06:03.829
(does hand movements)

00:06:03.829 --> 00:06:07.633
And two grown-ups will chase
each other through the halls.

00:06:07.633 --> 00:06:08.734
And it's his entertainment.

00:06:08.734 --> 00:06:10.302
We're around
for entertainment.

00:06:10.302 --> 00:06:13.606
<i>Now you'll notice that he never
 really quite looked at me.</i>

00:06:13.606 --> 00:06:14.707
<i> And it was intentional.</i>

00:06:14.707 --> 00:06:15.808
<i> No matter what I did,</i>

00:06:15.808 --> 00:06:17.242
<i> I could never get him
 to make eye contact.</i>

00:06:17.242 --> 00:06:20.345
<i> He is a very, very cool guy
 and very, very sharp.</i>

00:06:20.345 --> 00:06:22.482
<i> And I'm glad to have gone
 and done it.</i>

00:06:22.482 --> 00:06:24.950
<i> On the other extreme
 of this, this is Whack.</i>

00:06:24.950 --> 00:06:28.153
<i> She's a New Caledonian Crow,
 lives in Oxford, England.</i>

00:06:28.153 --> 00:06:30.622
<i> When she's not trying to poke
 the eyes out of visiting</i>

00:06:30.622 --> 00:06:33.091
<i> National Geographic
 photographers,</i>

00:06:33.091 --> 00:06:34.726
<i> which she did for two days,</i>

00:06:34.726 --> 00:06:36.728
<i> she excels at problem solving.</i>

00:06:36.728 --> 00:06:40.299
Creating tools from materials
she's never seen before,

00:06:40.299 --> 00:06:42.601
to solve problems she's
never been presented before.

00:06:42.601 --> 00:06:45.671
An example is,
they would take a test-tube and

00:06:45.671 --> 00:06:48.407
put something that she wanted
at the bottom of it, food.

00:06:48.407 --> 00:06:51.143
And present her with things
that you could make tools from.

00:06:51.143 --> 00:06:52.811
Now, what they didn't
know to this point,

00:06:52.811 --> 00:06:54.880
was that these animals
can make tools,

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:56.982
which is different than
using tools.

00:06:56.982 --> 00:07:00.152
Chimps do this, humans do this,
very few animals

00:07:00.152 --> 00:07:02.054
possess this capability.

00:07:02.054 --> 00:07:04.557
And Whack could
take something and

00:07:04.557 --> 00:07:07.159
fashion a tool from it to
reach into the test-tube

00:07:07.192 --> 00:07:09.762
and get the thing out of it,
that you were looking for

00:07:09.762 --> 00:07:12.198
from something she'd never
been presented before.

00:07:12.198 --> 00:07:14.700
It's amazing stuff.

00:07:14.700 --> 00:07:15.735
<i> Now, this is Betsy.</i>

00:07:15.901 --> 00:07:19.505
<i> Betsy is so famous that
 that's not even her real name.</i>

00:07:19.505 --> 00:07:20.739
(laughter)

00:07:20.739 --> 00:07:23.742
<i> I'm not kidding. She's a
Border Collie living in Vienna.</i>

00:07:23.742 --> 00:07:26.712
<i> And she has the vocabulary
 of a toddler.</i>

00:07:26.712 --> 00:07:28.447
She can hear a word
once or twice,

00:07:28.447 --> 00:07:30.048
and know that
it means something.

00:07:30.048 --> 00:07:33.586
She can link photographs with
an object in the photograph.

00:07:33.586 --> 00:07:36.455
An example would be to show her
a photograph of a teddy bear.

00:07:36.455 --> 00:07:39.325
Let's say it's Randy, right.
And say, "Go find Randy."

00:07:39.325 --> 00:07:43.061
And send her into another room
full of these stuffed animals.

00:07:43.061 --> 00:07:45.231
She'll look around and
she's got-- she's pretty good,

00:07:45.231 --> 00:07:47.666
and she'll find the thing
in the photograph,

00:07:47.666 --> 00:07:48.834
bring it back to you.

00:07:48.834 --> 00:07:50.068
Two or three times, come back

00:07:50.068 --> 00:07:51.803
in six months,
she's got it locked in.

00:07:51.803 --> 00:07:53.839
It... It's an incredible thing.

00:07:53.839 --> 00:07:58.243
<i> We put Shanti here, she's a
 9,000-pound Asian elephant,</i>

00:07:58.243 --> 00:08:01.279
<i> we put her on an enormous
 white seamless background.</i>

00:08:01.279 --> 00:08:03.248
<i> You know, they are amongst
 the most intelligent animals,</i>

00:08:03.248 --> 00:08:04.850
<i> they grieve, mimic behavior,</i>

00:08:04.850 --> 00:08:07.119
<i> they have language abilities,
 memory.</i>

00:08:07.119 --> 00:08:09.922
But then they look in
the mirror, they see themselves.

00:08:09.922 --> 00:08:12.090
And it's a rare cognitive
accomplishment, that

00:08:12.090 --> 00:08:13.992
we know is only shared
by great apes

00:08:14.026 --> 00:08:15.728
and dolphins and some humans.

00:08:15.728 --> 00:08:18.030
(audience roaring
with laughter)

00:08:18.030 --> 00:08:20.466
At the Bronx Zoo, elephants
were put in front of mirrors.

00:08:20.466 --> 00:08:22.468
And at first they treated
the mirror as an object

00:08:22.468 --> 00:08:23.702
as you might imagine.

00:08:23.702 --> 00:08:25.771
But then, they started
to check themselves out.

00:08:25.771 --> 00:08:27.740
They'd lift their trunks and
they would look at things

00:08:27.740 --> 00:08:29.074
and different places.

00:08:29.074 --> 00:08:31.944
See, for the longest time
science could just never accept

00:08:31.944 --> 00:08:34.947
what most pet owners know,
is that animals think and feel.

00:08:34.947 --> 00:08:38.517
But proving, proving that they
have thoughts and emotions

00:08:38.517 --> 00:08:40.385
is a lot of what
this work is about.

00:08:40.385 --> 00:08:42.988
And the scientists can
consider this a collaboration

00:08:42.988 --> 00:08:44.289
between them and the animals.

00:08:44.289 --> 00:08:47.460
Their work teaches us about
the boundaries of humanity.

00:08:47.493 --> 00:08:50.696
It's really exciting stuff but
it's about these characteristics

00:08:50.696 --> 00:08:53.032
that are distinctly human
and things that aren't.

00:08:53.032 --> 00:08:56.234
<i> This is a lemur at Duke.
 His name is Aristides, and</i>

00:08:56.234 --> 00:08:58.070
<i> they used to think these
 guys were not so smart.</i>

00:08:58.103 --> 00:09:00.138
<i> They are primates but
 they are on the lower end.</i>

00:09:00.138 --> 00:09:02.307
<i> But he learns
 like a toddler does.</i>

00:09:02.307 --> 00:09:03.342
<i> He is learning how to count.</i>

00:09:03.342 --> 00:09:04.976
<i> He uses a touch screen
 with his nose.</i>

00:09:04.976 --> 00:09:06.878
And all this stuff is
food rewards, right?

00:09:06.878 --> 00:09:09.915
So you do this right,
the sequence...
you get something,

00:09:09.915 --> 00:09:12.150
but they, they have
great enthusiasm for it,

00:09:12.184 --> 00:09:15.087
so they don't need to be fed.
They just like to do it.

00:09:15.087 --> 00:09:18.990
<i> And rats, they may or may
 not have a sense of humor,
 but they laugh.</i>

00:09:18.990 --> 00:09:22.661
<i>There's a guy at Bowling Green,
 his name is Jaak Panksepp.</i>

00:09:22.661 --> 00:09:24.530
<i> And they call him
 the rat tickler.</i>

00:09:24.530 --> 00:09:27.633
He takes rats, and
he tickles them, and they laugh.

00:09:27.633 --> 00:09:29.334
(laughter)

00:09:29.334 --> 00:09:30.669
So, they are trying to figure...

00:09:30.669 --> 00:09:33.505
They play jokes
on each other and stuff.

00:09:33.505 --> 00:09:34.906
<i> And there's not a day
 that goes by</i>

00:09:34.906 --> 00:09:36.642
<i> we don't learn something
 about honey bees, right.</i>

00:09:36.642 --> 00:09:38.643
<i> They are really,
 highly evolved socially,</i>

00:09:38.643 --> 00:09:40.278
<i> and they have
 this complex behavior</i>

00:09:40.278 --> 00:09:41.880
<i>of communication and navigation.</i>

00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:43.849
<i> They learn colors and scents.</i>

00:09:43.849 --> 00:09:46.017
<i> And they can map
 their environment out.</i>

00:09:46.017 --> 00:09:48.154
All with a brain
the size of a milligram.

00:09:48.154 --> 00:09:49.355
It's a little, tiny thing.

00:09:49.355 --> 00:09:51.657
And, and now according
to some work we think--

00:09:51.657 --> 00:09:53.492
we find out
they might have emotions.

00:09:53.492 --> 00:09:56.728
They might possess
pessi-- pessimism.

00:09:56.728 --> 00:09:58.898
<i> This is a Scrub Jay
 called Psychobird.</i>

00:09:58.898 --> 00:10:00.765
(laughter)

00:10:00.765 --> 00:10:02.834
<i> And they plan for the future.</i>

00:10:02.834 --> 00:10:04.770
<i> They take these birds, and
when they go to sleep at night.</i>

00:10:04.770 --> 00:10:06.939
<i> And wake up
 in two different rooms.</i>

00:10:06.939 --> 00:10:09.508
And in one room, in the morning
they feed them breakfast.

00:10:09.508 --> 00:10:11.076
And in the other room,
they don't.

00:10:11.076 --> 00:10:14.246
And after a while they give them
the option to feed at night.

